h institutions, the book is a collection of critical narratives that collectively show the diversity of faculty of color, attentive to and beyond race. The book is organized into three major parts comprised of chapters in which faculty of color depict how first-generation college student identities continue to inform how minoritized people navigate academe well into their professional careers, and encourage them to reconceptualize research, teaching, and service responsibilities to better consider the families and communities that shaped their lives well before college.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFirst-generation college studentszUnited States. 0aMinority college teacherszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  apeople of color, race politics, working class americans, american workers, blue collar jobs, marginalized communities, hispanic people in the workplace, hispanic workers, black workers, african american workers, asian workers, first generation immigrants, immigrant struggle, racism in the workplace, racism case studies, resources for faculty, faculty training books, first generation students, racial tokenization, first-generation faculty, faculty diversity.1 aAguilar-Hernández, José M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnaldo Jr., Constancio R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnaldo, Constancio R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuenavista, Tracy Lachica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuenavista, Tracy Lachica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCalderón, Dolores, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamangian, Patrick Roz, econtrib